<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Inexperience and &quot;throwing stuff into the market&quot;]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12495&amp;p=143582#p143582"><![CDATA[
Being an embedded systems guy myself, I see this issue both in software and in hardware.  A REALLY good example in the hardware realm is the state of the average donor cart based &quot;reproduction&quot; cart you see, or also the quality of work by people getting paid to do console mods.  There are very few people willing to take the time to learn to do it right, and for every Markfritzb or infiniteneslives there are dozens of idiots who don't know a soldering iron from a wood engraver.  Or back to Drag's original point about Arduinos, it astounds me when I see people selling completed projects where they're literally selling pre-programmed Arduino boards, rather than designing a board for their own actual application.  It increases the cost tenfold, it's almost always HUGE and it's just super tacky.  I mean, sure there has to be a learning curve for everything, but part of that learning curve should be knowing when a product isn't release-worthy.  Unfortunately, I think a lot of that would be best taught in a mentorship/apprenticeship learning paradigm, which is pretty much the exact opposite of the way most people learn these days...<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5348">qwertymodo</a> — Mon Mar 23, 2015 12:55 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
