<author><name><![CDATA[GradualGames]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-03-22T19:33:13-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-03-22T19:33:13-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12495&amp;p=143574#p143574</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12495&amp;p=143574#p143574"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Inexperience and &quot;throwing stuff into the market&quot;]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12495&amp;p=143574#p143574"><![CDATA[
I've had quite a journey myself in this regard. I started coding in '96 in QBasic. I was part of the QB RPGs craze. I knew *absolutely nothing,* except some extreme basics of putting together a simple scrolling engine in mode 13h. Naturally at age 16 I thought this meant I was some kind of god coder. This completely wrong self perception continued through college, and I still knew nothing. I took my first job. I still hadn't learned anything, helped develop some of the worst software I think I've ever seen in my entire life. Probably will never see anything worse. The industry wants people *that* badly. Yet I kept trying. Then I found my way to NES homebrew. Still knew almost jack squat. Once I began to build Nomolos, I started to learn a bit more about how software should be put together. I made a lot of mistakes. The game has tons of flaws. I released it. Now I'm working on another game. It too has flaws but it's much better than the last. I'm looking forward to releasing it.<br /><br />I dunno if I belong in the same category as people who slap together yet another god awful app in the play store (probably not, and maybe that was the origin of this thread anyway), but...there's no question, I have benefited greatly from actually building and releasing things. I'm a much better coder today than I was in say 2008 or so.<br /><br />On a different note, I do find a lot of digital distribution platforms annoying sometimes just in terms of the sheer volume of crap that gets released. Perhaps the feeling is that a large number of those people *don't even care* about becoming better programmers. That certainly isn't true in my case!<br /><br />In the words of G.K. Chesterton, &quot;a thing worth doing is worth doing badly.&quot; I think I might never have released my first game nor would I be close to finishing my second game if I didn't take that to heart. I don't consider it to be mutually exclusive with its counterpart &quot;a thing worth doing is worth doing well,&quot; either.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3735">GradualGames</a> — Sun Mar 22, 2015 7:33 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
