<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />If it is harmful for &quot;inexperienced coders [to] throw[] stuff into the market&quot;, then how are they supposed to become experienced in the first place?<br /></div><br />I'm seeing a lot of indies actually releasing the first game they ever made. As in, they didn't even try making non-commercial games before for practicing, or even any proper project aside from college homework, really. By general rule, that rarely pans out well.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />If only full-time employment counts as experience, then I have zero video game development experience. And it appears <a href="http://www.sloperama.com/advice/m83.htm" class="postlink">common for video game studio HR departments to apply that standard</a>:<br /></div><br />Making games on your own may give you experience when it comes to developing, but gives you absolutely zero experience with working constantly with a sizable team, and if it isn't full time then chances are you never dealt with stuff like crunch either (which like it or not is still extremely common, if not even the norm).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4526">Sik</a> — Sat Mar 14, 2015 1:13 am</p><hr />
